  "why": "DRFuzz explicitly steers its search toward inducing regression faults (inputs where the prior model predicts correctly but the regression model predicts incorrectly) by amplifying prediction differences between versions and by rewarding mutations that increase such differences. This is a defined, broader failure class (regression faults / any change from correct->incorrect), not an attacker-specified, predefined target output (e.g., forcing a specific target label or a particular malicious functionality). The paper repeatedly describes guiding mutations to maximize prediction-probability differences and measuring diversity across (cM1 -> cM2) behaviors, but it does not define or optimize for attacker-chosen target outputs. Therefore the approach aims at a broad class of safety/security-violating behaviors (regression faults) rather than targeted attack discovery.",
